ifornia, Markens explores how discourses about gender, family, race, genetics, rights, and choice have shaped policies aimed at this issue. She examines the views of key players, including legislators, women's organizations, religious groups, the media, and others. In a study that finds surprising ideological agreement among those with opposing views of surrogate motherhood, Markens challenges common assumptions about our responses to reproductive technologies and at the same time offers a fascinating picture of how reproductive politics shape social policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSurrogate motherhoodxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSurrogate motherhood. 0aSurrogate mothersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aSurrogate mothersxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aamerican politics.  acalifornia.  achildren.  achoice.  acultural studies.  aculture wars.  afamily.  afertility.  agender studies.  agenetics.  ahuman rights.  alegislation.  amedia coverage.  amorality.  amotherhood.  amothering.  anew york.  anewborn.  apolitical.  apro choice position.  aprocreation.  arace studies.  areligious groups.  areproduction.  areproductive politics.  areproductive studies.  areproductive technology.  asocial policy.  asurrogacy bills.  asurrogacy.  asurrogate motherhood.  asurrogate parenting.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025203540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094097040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940970423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940970/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Back